# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: afl-europe-championship
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:afl-europe-championship/2013-afl-europe-championship] The **2013 AFL Europe Championship** was a 16-a-side Australian rules football competition held in Dublin, Ireland between European countries.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2013-afl-europe-championship] This was the second AFL Europe Championship, run by AFL Europe.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2013-afl-europe-championship] Matches were played at DCU Sportsground in northern Dublin.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2013-afl-europe-championship] Contested between six national teams, the Championships were won by Ireland.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] It took place in Baku, Azerbaijan, from 12 to 28 June 2015, and featured almost 6,000 athletes from 50 countries competing in 30 sports, including 15 summer Olympic and 2 non-Olympic sports.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] Baku was awarded the right to host the first European Games at the 41st EOC General Assembly in Rome, on 8 December 2012.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] The European Games would take place every four years thereafter, with the next competition held in 2019.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] The decision was made as a result of secret balloting, where of 48 votes, 38 were in favour of the sole bidder for the event.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] Eight votes were against, and two more abstained from voting.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] The representatives of Armenia refused to take part in the voting.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] The Organising Committee responsible for the inaugural European Games in Baku was established by decree of the president of the Republic of Azerbaijan.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] The committee is chaired by the First Lady of Azerbaijan Mehriban Aliyeva, member of the Executive Committee of the National Olympic Committee of the Republic of Azerbaijan and UNESCO Goodwill Ambassador.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] Baku 2015 European Games Operations Committee (BEGOC) was established under the direction of the chairperson of the Organising Committee.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] The Chief Executive Officer of BEGOC is Azad Rahimov, Minister of Youth and Sport while the Chief Operating Officer is Simon Clegg.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] There were four clusters and 18 competition venues for the inaugural European Games, including 12 that were designed to become permanent venues.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] Five of the venues were new-builds: the National Gymnastics Arena, BMX Velopark, Baku Aquatics Centre, Baku Shooting Centre and National Stadium.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] There were six temporary venues: Water Polo Arena, Beach Arena, Basketball Arena, Mountain Bike Velopark, Triathlon, Cycling road race and time trial.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] The Athletes Village, located in the Nizami raion of Baku, comprises 13 buildings, 16 different types of apartments with three to four bedrooms per apartment.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] The local organising committee launched an online sales page on its website to allow fans purchasing tickets for the inaugural event.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] Adult tickets for sport sessions range between AZN 2 – AZN 5, according to competition round (for example preliminary or final), seat category, and venue.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] Organisers aimed to recruit 12,500 volunteers to play roles during the Games, including assisting athletes and dignitaries, working at sport competitions, or providing assistance to spectators or the media.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] Baku 2015 European Games volunteers were called Flamekeepers.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] 6,000 Ceremonies Performers voluntarily took part in the opening and closing ceremonies.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] The closing ceremony was held on 28 June in the National Stadium.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] James Hadley was the artistic director and Christian Steinhäuser the music director of the closing ceremony.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] 50 national olympic committees participated in this European Games edition, including the Olympic Committee of Kosovo in its first time at a wide multi-sport event.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] Since the Faroe Islands and Gibraltar are not members of the European Olympic Committee, the Faroese participants occurred for the Ligue Européenne de Natation and the Gibraltar participants for the Athletic Association of Small States of Europe.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] A total of 20 sports were represented: 16 Olympic sports, two Olympic sports contested only in non-Olympic formats (basketball and football) and two non-Olympic sports (karate and sambo).
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] Two para-sport events were contested judo.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] Twelve of the sports (archery, athletics, boxing, cycling, judo, shooting, swimming, table tennis, taekwondo, triathlon, volleyball, wrestling) would offer qualification opportunities for the Rio 2016 Summer Olympics.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] The aquatic sports are only open to junior-level competitors, and the athletics competition forms the third division of the European Team Championships.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] The competition schedule consists of 253 events.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] The International Sports Broadcasting (ISB) and Olympic Broadcasting Services are the host broadcasters of the European Games.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] During the Games, ISB was anticipated to produce 800 hours of broadcast coverage.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] Amnesty International have been a vocal critic of the Baku 2015 European Games, stating in March 2015, "Azerbaijan may be a safe country for athletes taking part in the 100 metres, but defending rights and free speech is a dangerous game here.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] Those who champion them receive harassment and prison sentences instead of medals.".
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] In August 2014, the human rights organisation highlighted the 24 prisoners of conscience being held in Azerbaijan prisons as an example of abuses.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] Western countries also criticized Aliyev's intention to close the OSCE offices in Baku.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] In June 2015, *The Guardian* reported that its own reporters, along with those of other media outlets, had been barred from entering Baku to cover the games.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] Human Rights Watch, in the same article, stated it had observed "the worst crackdown the country has seen in the post-Soviet era".
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] Most European heads of state and government refused to participate at the opening ceremony, sending mid- or low-level representatives instead.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] Among those who did participate were Vladimir Putin of Russia, Recep Tayyip Erdoğan of Turkey, Aleksander Lukashenko of Belarus, Boyko Borisov of Bulgaria and Victor Ponta of Romania.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] Ponta and Borisov faced criticism at home for their participation.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] During the games there was a road accident where a coach driver drove into a group of young Austrian athletes by mixing up the accelerator and brake pedals, with the incident recorded by a surveillance camera.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] 15-year-old Austrian synchronized swimmer Vanessa Sahinovic and her teammates Lisa Breit and Luna Pajer were injured.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] Sahinovic was placed in an induced coma and flown to Vienna for emergency surgery.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] Sahinovic was left paraplegic in the accident.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] Because of the accident, Austria had to withdraw from the team competition.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] In the synchronized swimming duet competition, sisters Anna-Maria and Eirini-Maria Alexandri won the silver medal, which they dedicated to the injured teammates.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] The police officer who released the video of the surveillance camera was relieved of his duties.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] Sahinovic is recovering, and is supported by an initiative of Austrian swimmers and a fundraising campaign.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] The official logo for the 2015 European Games was unveiled on 16 June 2014.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] Designed by Adam Yunusov, it was inspired by country's contemporary culture.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] The logo includes flame, water, the mythical Simurgh bird, an Azerbaijani carpet and a pomegranate as one of the symbols of Azerbaijani profusion.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] The pomegranate, called *Nar* (pomegranate in Azerbaijani), is one of two mascots for the Games, along with a gazelle named *Jeyran* (gazelle in Azerbaijani).
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] The couple are intended to represent the spirit of Azerbaijan and help excite the youth for the event.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] The brand incorporates traditional Azerbaijani imagery with images and colours designed to evoke a European sporting feel.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] The pomegranate tree, whose fruit juice is one of Azerbaijan's main exports, features heavily.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] The brand was created with legacy potential in mind, possibly inspired by the way the Commonwealth Games’ branding retains a similar feel each year.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] As Azerbaijan as a state sponsored Spanish football club Atlético Madrid at that time, this European Games was advertised on the club's kits during the later half of their 2014–15 season.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] On 21 May 2014, Procter & Gamble became the first official partner of the inaugural European Games.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] Swiss watchmaker Tissot has been named the official timekeeper and will provide all timing and scoring services.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] On 13 November 2014, Motorola Solutions also teamed up with Baku 2015 as the Official Radio Communications Supporter.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] On Sunday 26 April the president of the Republic of Azerbaijan, Ilham Aliyev, captured the official flame of the Baku 2015 European Games.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2015-european-games] The flame had visited 60 locations until the final torchbearer entered the National Stadium for the Opening Ceremony on 12 June.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2016-afl-europe-championship] The **2016 AFL Europe Championship** was an 18-a-side Australian rules football competition held in London, United Kingdom between European countries.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2016-afl-europe-championship] This was the third AFL Europe Championship, run by AFL Europe.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2016-afl-europe-championship] Matches were played at Motspur Park in London.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2016-afl-europe-championship] Contested between four national teams, the Championships were won by Great Britain.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2018-european-championships] The **2018 European Championships** were the first edition of the European Championships.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2018-european-championships] It was a multi-sport event which took place in Berlin, Germany, and Glasgow, Scotland, United Kingdom (with Edinburgh hosting the diving events and Gleneagles the golf) from 2 to 12 August 2018.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2018-european-championships] Around 1,500 athletes competed at the European Athletics Championships in Berlin, whilst at the same time more than 3,000 took part in the other championships in Glasgow.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2018-european-championships] Each European Championship was organised by the respective federation and host city.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2018-european-championships] On 1 August, at the "Great Big Opening Party" in Glasgow, a new European Championship Trophy was unveiled, which was awarded to the nation achieving the most gold medals across all seven sports during the Championships.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2018-european-championships] It was presented by Katherine Grainger, Emma Fredh and Angelina Melnikova on behalf of the seven European federations involved in the event.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2018-european-championships] On 12 August, the trophy was presented to the leading nation on the overall table, Russia, in a ceremony in Glasgow.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2018-european-championships] The original schedule was released in February 2017.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2018-european-championships] The schedule was updated in June 2017 based on the Glasgow ticket schedule and again in March 2018 when the Berlin timetable was released.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2018-european-championships] Each sport maintained its own medal table, but an overall medal table is also maintained, the leader of which won the European Championship trophy.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2018-european-championships] Russia won the inaugural trophy and topped the medal table by gold medals won with 31, whilst co-hosts Great Britain topped the total medals table with 74 medals, 26 of which were gold.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2018-european-championships] A chasing pack consisting of Italy, the Netherlands, co-hosts Germany and France each won over 10 gold medals and 40 medals in total.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2018-european-championships] In addition, while both the Men's and Women's Gymnastics events included junior competitions in line with previous editions, medals in those competitions are not included within the total.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2018-european-championships] All of Europe's major free-to-air broadcasters televised the European Championships in 2018, such as BBC in the United Kingdom, ARD/ZDF in Germany, France Télévisions in France, RAI in Italy and TVE in Spain.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2018-european-championships] Other EBU members who signed up include VRT (Belgium), HRT (Croatia), DR (Denmark), YLE (Finland), RTÉ (Ireland), NOS (Netherlands), NRK (Norway), TVP (Poland), RTP (Portugal), SRG SSR (Switzerland) and SVT (Sweden).
[src:afl-europe-championship/2018-european-championships] The level of coverage was also enhanced by a deal with Eurosport.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2018-european-championships] In total, over 40 EBU members signed agreements as of April 2018.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2018-european-championships] There were discussions with broadcasters in the remaining territories in Europe, plus other global territories like China, Japan and USA.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2018-european-championships] Glasgow 2018 had five official partners (People Make Glasgow, Scottish Government, Strathmore Water, Spar & Eurovision) and Berlin 2018 had six official partners (Spar, Le Gruyère, Nike, Toyo Tires, Generali & Eurovision) with another tier of official supporters across the two host cities.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2018-european-championships] Overall over 56 companies signed up to support the inaugural event.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The games featured 200 events in 15 sports (23 disciplines).
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] Around 4,000 athletes from 50 countries participated.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] Ten of the sports offered qualification opportunities for the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo, Japan.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The opening ceremony at the Dinamo Stadium was held on 21 June, and the closing ceremony at the same venue was held on 30 June.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] A number of countries and cities expressed their interest to host the second European Games in 2019 but only the Netherlands submitted an official bid.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] At the meeting of an Extraordinary General Assembly on 16 May 2015, the Netherlands was unanimously approved as host of the second edition of the Games.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The competition intended to be nationwide and based in seven cities, including Amsterdam, The Hague, Eindhoven, Rotterdam, Utrecht.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] On 10 June 2015, the Netherlands announced their refusal to hold the second European Games after insufficient funding for the Games, projected to cost €57.5m.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The European Olympic Committee president, Patrick Hickey said the news was "disappointing".
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] Following this, a number of countries expressed interest in hosting the games: Belarus (Minsk), United Kingdom (Glasgow), Poland (Poznań), Russia (Kazan and Sochi), Turkey (Istanbul).
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] In November 2015, Russia was announced as a future host country for the II European Games.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] At the same time, the WADA began its investigation of the doping scandal in Russia which led to the IOC's refusal to support the holding of major sports events in Russia, including the second European Games.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] During the meeting of the EOC General Assembly, held in Minsk on 21 October 2016, Minsk was selected as a host city for the second European Games.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] On 12 May 2017, the President of Belarus Alexander Lukashenko signed a decree on the Foundation of the Directorate of the II European Games 2019.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The founders of the foundation are the National Olympic Committee, the Minsk City Executive Committee and the Ministry of Sports and Tourism.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] Georgy Katulin, General Secretary of the National Olympic Committee of the Republic of Belarus, was appointed the CEO of the foundation in August 2017.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] In November 2017, the management launched the official website of the games.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] In April 2019, Lukashenko announced that the Games were on budget and on time and that "everything should meet the highest standards".
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] Sergei Rumas, Belarus's prime minister and the head of the Organising Committee also said that all the facilities would be finished by 15 May and that "95 per cent of the equipment has already been installed".
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] On 20 May 2019, Lukashenko signed Decree No.191, entitled "On security measures during the 2nd European Games in Belarus".
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] It gave the Ministry of Defence the power to restrict access to certain areas and placed a ban on drones, unmanned aerial vehicles and model aeroplanes at competition venues.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] Drones and planes violating the decree will be seized until 2 July, when the Games end.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The start of the volunteer selection began in September 2017 during the "Dobrofest" and registration ended on 1 April 2019.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] In April 2019, the head of the volunteer network for the Games, Nadezhda Anisovets, said that the appeal resulted in 24,000 applications, much larger than the 8,000 needed for the Games.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] Most of them are students of Belarusian universities.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] Applications were also received from 52 other countries including Russia, Australia, the USA, Mexico, and Egypt.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The basic requirements for the candidate are communication skills and high English-language proficiency.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The selected volunteers will be involved in over 34 functional areas.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] Each volunteer will be given a special uniform, badges and souvenirs.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] On June 30, 2019, Tony Moore performed his composition “We Are The Light” at the closing ceremony of the European Games 2019 in Belarus.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The song was written to honour the 8000 volunteers who helped host the Euro Games in Minsk 2019.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] On 27 December 2017, it was announced about the finalising of the development of a comprehensive transport service plan for the competition, based on the needs of all stakeholders and the experience of the previous Olympic and European Games host cities: Beijing, London, Baku.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The main goal of the developed plan is to optimise the routes in such a way that any participant can get to any stadium in no more than half an hour.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] Rail services between Masyukovshchina (Minsk-Arena), Belarus (regatta course Zaslawye) and Loshitsa (Čyžoŭka-Arena) will operate with higher frequency during the event.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] In addition, the existing bus network will be expanded by 10 to 12 new routes to the competition sites, which will run up to 300 buses and trolleybuses.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] In August 2018, new digital information boards were unveiled in order to improve the public transport network for foreign visitors.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] Valery Shkuratov, the director of Metropolitan Transport and Communications (the firm which manage the transit systems in the city), said that more than 270 displays had already been installed.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] In October 2018, it was announced that the Minsk metro would have full 4G coverage by the time the Games began.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The next month, fourteen taxi companies in Minsk as well as several governmental and administrational departments signed a memorandum of understanding to guarantee fair prices during the Games.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] In March 2019, it was announced that the taxis adhering to the scheme would carry a logo to enable customers to identify them.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The Organising committee plans to involve already existed sports facilities after their renovation.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The Opening and closing ceremonies, as well as competitions in track and field, will be held at the Dinamo Stadium (Minsk, Kirov, 8).
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] Athletes, team officials and other team personnel will stay on the grounds of Minsk University, which has the capacity to host up to 7,500 people.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The students have been evicted for the duration of the Games and given alternative accommodation.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] Part of the village facilities has already been put into operation, part of it will be completed by April 2019.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] Each apartment has two bedrooms and can hold up to 4 people.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The village also has a canteen, gym, merchandise store and cultural centre.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The torch relay "Flame of Peace" was planned for before the games.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] In addition to traditional running with a torch, there were also creative performances organised along the route.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The torch relay will last for 50 days and will cover 7,700 km.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The relay will include 450 torchbearers, 100 volunteers and 10 flame keepers.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The torch relay will begin on 3 May in Rome.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The torch itself was designed by Yulia Braychuk, weighs 1.7 kg and is 81 cm tall.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] It is made from stainless steel and can be attached to a bike or wheelchair.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] All fifty European Olympic Committees member countries competed at the Games.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] Numbers in brackets denote the number of athletes being sent to the Games.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The Opening ceremony was held at National Olympic Stadium Dinamo and ran from 22:10 to 00:45 FET.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] It was produced by Russian company Art City 5, and was directed by Alexander Vavilov (Belarus) and Alexei Sechenov (Russia).
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] Augmented reality imagery was used during the ceremony.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The main musical performers were Anna Netrebko, Ilya Silchukov with Elena Salo and Dimash Kudaibergen.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] During the parade of nations, Greece entered the stadium first.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The host nation Belarus marched last, while other countries entered in English alphabetical order.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] Each delegation is escorted by girls in dresses representing the Kupala wheel, a symbol of the sun for Eastern Slavs decorated with traditional Belarusian ornaments.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] Georgian President Salome Zourabichvili, who was due to attend the ceremony, left early due to the civil unrest in the Georgian capital of Tbilisi.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] A total of 15 sports were presented: archery, athletics, badminton, 3x3 basketball, beach football, boxing, canoe sprint, cycling, gymnastics, judo, karate, sambo, shooting, table tennis and wrestling.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] A number of disciplines were dropped after the 2015 European Games: all aquatics (diving, swimming, synchronised swimming and water polo), BMX racing, mountain biking, fencing, taekwondo, triathlon and all volleyball (beach volleyball and indoor volleyball).
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The competition schedule consists of 200 events.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The Closing ceremony was held at National Olympic Stadium Dinamo and ran from 22:00 to 23:50 FET.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] In attendance were IOC President Thomas Bach, Russian President Vladimir Putin, Tajik President Emomali Rahmon, and Armenian President Armen Sarkissian.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The prototype for creating the 2nd European Games' logo in Minsk was the Kupala fire and "paparats-kvetka", which plays an important role in .
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The logo of the Games was "paparać-kvietka" (Belarusian: папараць-кветка, romanized: *paparats-kvyetka*)—a plant that plays an important role in the culture of the Slavic culture.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] According to legend, the mythical flower blossoms once a year at midnight on Kupala Night.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] Anyone who sees this flowering will become the owner of unusual abilities and talents.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The slogan of the event is "Bright Year, Bright You", which also makes reference to the national domain of the Republic of Belarus and the official international shortening—BY.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] In autumn of 2017, an open republican contest for the development of the mascot of the European Games was announced.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] Anyone could take part in the competition.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] Over 2,000 variants were collected from professionals and amateurs.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The public presentation of the winning version took place in Minsk on 29 November 2018.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The mascot chosen was a baby fox named "Lesik" who wears a shirt and shorts with the colours of the games' logo and wears shoes and a baseball hat with the games' slogan.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] Lesik's story is based after The Little Prince, when after the Little Prince leaves Earth, Lesik the Fox misses his new friend and wants to make more.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] He learns of a legendary flower called the Paparats Kvetka which can help his dream come true, but he needs to travel 1 million steps to Belarus to find it.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] He represents friendship, development, harmony, discipline, determination, cheerfulness, invincibility and vigour, according to the mascot's creators.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The slogan of the event is "Bright Year, Bright You!", which also successfully points to the national domain of the Republic of Belarus and the official international abbreviation BY.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] Sponsorship was approved as one of the sources to reduce the number of budgetary funds for the games according to the decree of the President of the Republic of Belarus of 12 May 2017 «On the Directorate of the second European Games 2019».
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] On 15 December 2017, the official sponsor of the games became the operator of electronic interactive games «Sport Pari».
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] On 22 December 2017, it was announced that the telecommunication operator velcom is the official telecommunication partner of the 2nd European Games of 2019.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] In March 2019, the Games' Organising Committee signed a memorandum of understanding with UNAIDS to strengthen co-operation in promoting safe lifestyles, preventing the spread of HIV/AIDS and eliminating discrimination around the infection.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The deadline for submitting the selfie photos was October 2018.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The criteria for evaluating photos include compliance with the theme and conditions of the contest, as well as artistic taste and originality.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The final results were to be announced in late December 2018; however, the competition was extended to the 31 December.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] It was then later announced that the deadline would be extended again to the 25 February 2019.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The winners were awarded diplomas from Belteleradiocompany, as well as sets of tickets for the events of the European Games in Minsk and the official gear of the National Team of the Republic of Belarus.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] It happened on 21 June, nearly 30 minutes prior to Opening Ceremony of the Games.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] On 1 February 2019, Belposhta, the Belarusian postal service, released the official stamps for the Games.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The four designs depict a cyclist, a runner, a rower and a dancer and were designed by Marina Vitkovskaya, with 120,000 sets being printed.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] There was an official cancellation ceremony in Minsk City Hall on the day of release.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] In February 2019, International Sports Broadcasting, a Spanish firm, was chosen as the host broadcaster for the Games, beating Match TV and Medialuso-Mediapro.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] The company had previously broadcast the 1st European Games in Baku.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] In March 2019, ISB was allowed to sell global broadcasting rights for the Games, with around 117 countries that have already been granted viewing rights.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2019-european-games] ISB and the Games' organisers have expressed that they hope to broadcast to more than 160 countries.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2022-european-championships] The **2022 European Championships** were the second edition of the European Championships.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2022-european-championships] It was a multi-sport event which took place in Munich, Germany from 11 to 21 August 2022.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2022-european-championships] The event started three days after the closing ceremonies of the Commonwealth Games held in Birmingham, Great Britain.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2022-european-championships] Athletics, cycling, triathlon, women's artistic gymnastics, men's artistic gymnastics and rowing returned after appearing in the inaugural Championships in 2018.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2022-european-championships] New to this edition of the Championships were beach volleyball, canoe sprint, and, for the first time, a full slate of para-sport events, sport climbing and table tennis.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2022-european-championships] Unlike the 2018 European Championships, swimming, diving, artistic swimming and open water swimming were not part of the program of the event, as the European Aquatics Championships were held at the same time but in Rome, Italy.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2022-european-championships] Golf, in the form of the European Golf Team Championships, did not return for this edition.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2022-european-championships] As a result of the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, athletes from Russia and Belarus were banned from competing at the 2022 European Championships.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2022-european-championships] Two athletes participated as the Athlete Refugee Team.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2022-european-championships] The five British competitors in table tennis were listed as representing England.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2022-european-championships] One athlete was listed as representing World Triathlon.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] The **3rd European Games** (Polish: *III Igrzyska Europejskie, Igrzyska Europejskie 2023*), also known as the **2023 European Games** or **Kraków-Małopolska 2023**, was an international multi-sport event held from 21 June to 2 July 2023 in Kraków and Małopolska, Poland.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] It was the first time that Poland hosted the European Games.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] All Olympic sports held at the European Games provided qualification opportunities for the 2024 Summer Olympics in Paris, France.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] At the time of the 2015 European Games, the city of Manchester, United Kingdom expressed its wish to host the 2023 Games.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] No further interest was expressed since after the 2018 European Championships were awarded to Glasgow, Scotland and the 2022 Commonwealth Games were awarded to Birmingham, England.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] In May 2018, the European Olympic Committees (EOC) asserted that the bidding process for the 2023 Games would be open to joint bids from multiple countries.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] The EOC launched the bid process on 20 September 2018 after a meeting of the constituent National Olympic Committees in Stockholm.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] Following the approval of the Bid Document, it was sent to the 50 NOCs in Europe alongside a letter from EOC President Janez Kocijančič inviting applications.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] The application stage was set to close on 28 February 2019.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] In January 2019, Marcin Krupa, the mayor of Katowice, Poland, announced the city's interest hosting the Games, becoming the first candidate city.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] Soon after, Kazan, the capital of Tatarstan, Russia expressed its interest in hosting the 2023 Games and its intention to submit an application to the EOC.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] Its bid would be made attractive by the fact the city built much sporting infrastructure when hosting the 2013 Summer Universiade and the 2015 FINA World Aquatics Championships and that a Russian bid has been supported by premier Vladimir Putin.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] In February 2019, the application deadline was extended by two months, until 30 April, due to "strong interest from across the continent".
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] In May 2019, after the extended deadline had passed, the EOC again postponed the deadline, this time until the 31 May.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] No reason was given for the second extension.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] In May 2019, the Polish Olympic Committee announced that Kraków would replace Katowice as the Polish bid for the Games following the withdrawal of its bid for the 2022 Winter Olympics and the waning interest in Katowice.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] The same month, EOC President Janez Kocijančič reiterated his expectation that the host for the 2023 Games would be chosen before the start of the 2019 European Games in Minsk on the 21 June 2019.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] After the deadline for bid submission passed on the 31 May 2019, the European Olympic Committees confirmed that only one formal bid had been completed, that of Kraków in collaboration with the province Małopolska.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] The mayor of Kraków, Jacek Majchrowski, had previously said that the city might decline to run the Games without support from regional and national government.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] The official election of the European Games 2023 host took place at an EOC General Assembly in Minsk on 22 June 2019 where it was unanimously decided that Kraków and the surrounding Lesser Poland region would hold the Games.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] The contract with the host city was signed on 17 May 2022.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] On 28 June 2019, six days after Kraków was awarded the Games, the EOC confirmed it had signed a letter of intent with the European Union of Gymnastics to include gymnastics in the upcoming Games.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] In July 2019, Hasan Arat, the vice-president of the Turkish Olympic Committee, was named chair of the EOC's Co-ordination Commission for the 2023 Games.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] He said he was "honoured and humbled by the decision".
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] In October the same year, both the city of Kraków and the Małopolska region signed a letter of intent confirming their joint commitment to the hosting of the Games.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] In March 2020, Kraków's mayor Jacek Majchrowski warned of cuts to the city budget and impacts on the tourism industry due to coronavirus which could impact the success of the Games.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] In February 2021, the Games faced a funding deadlock when the city of Kraków said it needed financial guarantees from the Polish government in order to proceed with the signing of the host city contract.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] A spokesperson of the office of the mayor of Kraków, Jacek Majchrowski, said that the city had agreed to host the Games "only on condition that the government subsidised the necessary infrastructure".
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] Government organisers blamed the city's leadership, with Jacek Sasin saying that "Kraków is the organiser of the Games" and that the government is "ready" to support it.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] Sasin said that the government would commit to sharing funding, but only after Kraków signed the host city contract.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] However, Majchrowski said that he would not sign the agreement until the government has introduced legislation supporting the event's organisation, leading to suggestions that Katowice, the original bid city, and the Silesia region could end up hosting the Games.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] In a statement, the EOC said they were "working closely with the organisers" and remained "confident" that Kraków would sign the host city contract.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] In early March 2021, the EOC entered into talks with Silesian officials to explore the possibility of the region co-hosting the event.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] Kraków and the Polish government were reported to have come to an agreement over funding by the end of March 2021.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] The opening ceremony was held at Henryk Reyman Municipal Stadium and ran from 20:30 to 23:45 CEST.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] An Esports European Games in Katowice, recognised by the EOC, was also held alongside the Games, but did not form part of the Kraków 2023 program.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] Events took place in the city of Kraków, the surrounding Lesser Poland Voivodeship region and in Bielsko-Biała and Chorzów in the neighbouring Silesian Voivodeship.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] The official emblem of the games was unveiled on 21 June 2022, exactly one year before the opening ceremony.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] Designed by Marcin Salawa the emblem depicts a flame containing the towers of St.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] Mary's Basilica, to represent the city of Kraków and the Tatra Mountains, to represent the landscape of the Małopolska region.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] The colours, taken from the coats of arms of Kraków, and Małopolska, represent fire and water.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] Fire is said to symbolise action, will, energy, while water symbolises spirituality, emotions and purification.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] The official motto of the games is *We are Unity*, Polish: *Jesteśmy jednością*, lit.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] “Krakusek” the dragon and “Sandra” the salamander have been chosen as the official mascots for the European Games Kraków-Małopolska 2023.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] The initiative, which received over 2,400 entries, was open to young people aged 5–15 across the continent.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] The dragon design by 15-year-old Katarzyna Biśta from Libiąż references the local culture and history of Kraków.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] Alongside Krakusek, the creation of the black and gold salamander by 10-year-old Gloria Goryl from Wojnicz portrays the fire salamander which can be found in south Poland.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] On 6 July 2021, Atos has been selected by the European Olympic Committees as its official Digital Technology Partner for the 2023 and 2027 editions of the European Games.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] As part of this partnership, Atos, long-standing supporter of the Olympic Movement, and EOC, the governing body for Europe's 50 National Olympic Committees, will work together to improve fan engagement.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] On November 14 2022, representatives of LaLiga and the European Games Organising Committee signed a cooperation agreement to mutually promote sports events and organisations.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] 50 countries around the world will broadcast the European Games.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] The region of Małopolska, to which the Games were jointly awarded, declared itself an LGBT ideology-free zone in 2019.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] In August 2020, the Lord Provost of Edinburgh Frank Ross wrote to Kraków's mayor Jacek Majchrowski to confirm the city's opposition to homophobia after calls for a "serious rethink" of the two cities' twinning relationship.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] Flemish sports minister Ben Weyts said the region's LGBT-free zone declaration is "incompatible with the values of the Olympic Charter" and that Olympic Committees should not support bids from such regions.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] The EOC responded, saying that there would be "no discrimination of any kind" and that the Olympic Charter would be respected.
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] The Małopolska region revoked its declaration of an LGBT ideology-free zone on 27 September 2021 and instead adopted a resolution to "oppose any discrimination against anyone for any reason".
[src:afl-europe-championship/2023-european-games] The EOC did not allow athletes representing Russia and Belarus to attend the games as a result of the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:afl-europe-championship/afl-europe-championship] The **AFL Europe Championship** is a triennial international Australian football competition played between European national teams.
[src:afl-europe-championship/afl-europe-championship] The European Championship is played in a full traditional 18-a-side format (formerly 16-a-side) unlike the Euro Cup which has a 9-a-side format.
[src:afl-europe-championship/afl-europe-championship] It is organised by AFL Europe and held every three years.
[src:afl-europe-championship/afl-europe-championship] Eligibility is similar to the Australian Football International Cup with national team representatives restricted to nationals - citizens who were resident in the country between the ages of 10 and 16.
[src:afl-europe-championship/afl-europe-championship] The inaugural competition was played in Sweden and Denmark in August 2010.
[src:afl-europe-championship/afl-europe-championship] The 2013 championships were held in Ireland in August 2013.
[src:afl-europe-championship/afl-europe-championship] A women's division was added in 2016 which was won by host nation Great Britain.
[src:afl-europe-championship/afl-europe-championship] Historically the competition has been dominated by Great Britain and Ireland who between them have won every edition of the competition, both men's and women's, up to the 2022 tournament, while Germany and the Scandinavian teams have also featured regularly in the final phases.
